<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_dictionary` row that
    declares the `duration_to_close` Duration **function field** on the
    `x_casemgmt_case` custom table inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    This dictionary entry is the AAP-compliant fix for QA Checkpoint 4 finding
    Issue #1 ("avg_time_to_close.xml empty <aggregation_source/> element —
    widget cannot compute AVG, will display 'No data'"). It implements
    Option A (function field) from the original report file's documented
    remediation paths, scoped to a single dictionary entry that satisfies
    AAP Section 0.4.4 (Manager View Dashboard Widget 4 specification:
    "single-score widget for 'Average time to close' (computed as
    closed_date - opened_date over Closed cases)") AND AAP Section 0.7.3
    Validation Gate 6 ("All widgets display data; no broken report
    references").

    THIS FIELD'S ROLE IN THE OVERALL POC
    ====================================
    `duration_to_close` is a **ServiceNow Function Field**: a virtual
    (non-stored) field whose value is computed at query time by the
    platform's native database-level function `glidefunction:datediff`.
    Function fields differ from "Calculated Value" fields in two
    important ways:

      1) Function fields are reportable. Calculated Value fields are
         executed in JavaScript each time a row is read and cannot be
         used as a report aggregation source (per ServiceNow community
         guidance). Function fields, by contrast, push the computation
         to the database query layer and can be used in reports just
         like any other field — including as the `<aggregation_source>`
         on a `sys_report` of `<aggregate>AVG</aggregate>`.

      2) Function fields require no business rule, no Flow Designer
         subflow, no seed-data hook, and no calculation script. They
         re-evaluate themselves at every query against the row and
         always reflect the current values of their input fields
         (here, `opened_date` and `closed_date`).

    The Manager View dashboard's "Average Time to Close" single-score
    widget (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_manager_view.xml
    Widget 4) is powered by ../reports/x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml,
    whose `<aggregation_source>` element references THIS field
    (`duration_to_close`). At report execution time the platform issues
    a query equivalent to:

        SELECT AVG(datediff(closed_date, opened_date))
        FROM   x_casemgmt_case
        WHERE  status = 'Closed'

    yielding a single Duration-typed average that the dashboard widget
    renders as a human-readable interval (e.g., "5 days 03:42:11").

    WHY OPTION A (FUNCTION FIELD) AND NOT OPTION C (EMPTY SOURCE)
    =============================================================
    The original CP4 implementation chose Option C: leave
    `<aggregation_source/>` empty in the report XML and document the
    gap as a "POC limitation". QA Checkpoint 4 flagged this as MAJOR
    Issue #1 because it caused the widget to render the "No data"
    placeholder, violating Validation Gate 6's "All widgets display
    data" pass condition.

    The Option C rationale invoked AAP Section 0.7.2 "Minimal-Change
    Clause" + "stop and report" rule under the assumption that adding
    a derived field would expand scope beyond the AAP-enumerated
    schema. On closer reading, that assumption is incorrect:

      - AAP Section 0.7.2 Minimal-Change Clause prohibits adding
        "modules, workflows, portal pages, tables, or integrations
        beyond the defined scope". A function field on an existing,
        AAP-enumerated table is none of those: it is not a module,
        not a workflow, not a portal page, not a new table, and not
        an integration. It is a query-time derivation from existing
        AAP-enumerated columns (`opened_date`, `closed_date`).

      - AAP Section 0.5.1 dictionary inventory uses the wildcard
        `servicenow-case-management-poc/dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_*.xml`
        ("every dictionary entry on the case table"), which permits
        derived fields needed to satisfy other AAP requirements.

      - AAP Section 0.4.4 explicitly requires the Manager View widget
        to display "Average time to close (computed as
        closed_date - opened_date over Closed cases)" — i.e., it
        REQUIRES the computation to be performed and rendered. A
        derived field that performs exactly that computation is the
        AAP-mandated implementation, not a scope expansion.

      - AAP Section 0.7.3 Validation Gate 6 demands that "All widgets
        display data". An empty aggregation source produces a "No
        data" placeholder, which fails the Gate.

    Option A is therefore the AAP-compliant choice. This file
    implements it with the minimum possible footprint: one dictionary
    entry, no business rule, no script include, no seed-data
    coupling, no flow change.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java line 168-173:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_created", nullable = false,
                    insertable = true, updatable = false)
            @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)
            private Date created;
            @Column(name = "cm_case_closed")
            @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)
            private Date closed;
        ArkCase tracked the case-creation timestamp (`created`) and the
        case-closure timestamp (`closed`) on the same JPA entity. There
        was no derived `duration` column on `acm_case_file`; Pentaho
        SQL queries computed `TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND, cm_case_created,
        cm_case_closed)` at report-render time. The ServiceNow target
        replicates the same query-time-derivation pattern using the
        platform-native `glidefunction:datediff` operator on the pair
        (`opened_date`, `closed_date`) — preserving ArkCase's semantic
        of "duration is computed from the timestamps, not stored
        separately".
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseSummaryByStatusAndTime
        PeriodDto.java aggregated cases by status across time periods
        for Pentaho consumption. The function-field equivalent here is
        consumed by ../reports/x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml via
        native ServiceNow GlideAggregate, replacing the external BI
        engine per AAP Section 0.1.2.

    FIELD NAMING (`duration_to_close`)
    ==================================
    The field name is `duration_to_close` (lowercase, snake_case),
    NOT `duration_to_close_seconds`, `time_to_close`, or
    `case_duration`:

      - Lowercase snake_case matches every other field on the case
        table (`opened_date`, `closed_date`, `assigned_group`,
        `assigned_agent`, etc.) per AAP Section 0.5.7 Title Case
        column-label convention.
      - The suffix `_to_close` (rather than `_close`) reads
        naturally as "duration TO close" — i.e., the elapsed time
        until closure, paired symmetrically with the closure
        timestamp `closed_date`.
      - No `_seconds` suffix because the field is typed as
        `glide_duration` (a Duration, not an Integer-of-seconds).
        ServiceNow renders Duration values as human-readable
        intervals (e.g., "3 Days 12:34:56") and aggregates them
        natively in reports without requiring caller code to
        translate seconds <-> days.

    FUNCTION DEFINITION (`glidefunction:datediff(closed_date,opened_date)`)
    =======================================================================
    The ServiceNow function-field formula syntax is:
        glidefunction:<function_name>(<arg1>,<arg2>,...)

    For our use case:
        glidefunction:datediff(closed_date,opened_date)

    Argument order is significant. ServiceNow's `datediff` function
    returns the duration `arg1 - arg2`, expecting the LATER timestamp
    as the first argument and the EARLIER timestamp as the second
    argument; this convention yields a positive duration when the
    case has been closed (closed_date > opened_date). If the order
    were reversed (`datediff(opened_date,closed_date)`), the result
    would be negative for every Closed case and the AVG would be
    meaningless. The current order is therefore canonical for the
    "average time to close" semantic.

    Behavior on non-Closed cases:
      - If `closed_date` is empty (the case is still in Draft, Open,
        In Progress, Pending, or Resolved status), the function
        returns NULL.
      - The report's `<filter>status=Closed</filter>` element ensures
        only Closed cases participate in the AVG, so NULL durations
        are filtered out at the query level — the AVG is computed
        ONLY over the population of cases that have actually been
        closed, which is the AAP-correct semantic.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: `<name>` resolves to `x_casemgmt_case`
        within the scoped application, and `<sys_scope>` / `<sys_package>`
        bind THIS dictionary record to the same scope by `source` attribute
        lookup. NO global-scope writes. The function field operates only
        on `x_casemgmt_case` columns, never on out-of-the-box tables.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` resolve by scope source name (`x_casemgmt`).
        The `<sys_id>` text-node value is THIS record's own
        deterministic primary key (MD5 of the canonical field
        identifier `x_casemgmt_case.duration_to_close` =
        f08a56ae8a5263f0af629913c48ae173) and is NOT a reference to
        any other record. The deterministic derivation matches the
        sibling convention (closed_date sys_id =
        25c60a42b3b9a76ae153979ec5e88edc, opened_date sys_id =
        3e18b5498c00dfde143bbc84fced474c).
      - The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used per AAP convention (Section 0.7.2 "Scoped-namespace-only constraint"); ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the scope id is concrete in the XML before export.
      - mandatory=false at the dictionary level. A function field
        cannot be "mandatory" in the user-input sense because users
        cannot type values into it; the platform computes the value
        automatically from the input fields. The dictionary
        attribute is set to false to allow rows where the input
        fields (notably closed_date) are empty.
      - read_only=true at the dictionary level. Function fields are
        always read-only by definition: their value is derived from
        other fields and cannot be overwritten directly. Setting
        read_only=true is redundant with function_field=true but
        explicit for clarity and consistency with the read-only
        treatment of the input fields (`opened_date`, `closed_date`
        — both read_only=true per their respective dictionary
        entries).
      - audit=false. A function field has no persistent value to
        audit; the audit trail of the input fields (sys_updated_on
        when opened_date or closed_date last changed) already
        captures the lineage.
      - active=true: the field is part of the live schema from
        Update Set commit forward.
      - display=false: the duration value is not surfaced on the
        case form or list views. This matches AAP Section 0.7.4 —
        the field exists solely to power the Manager View
        dashboard's avg-time-to-close widget and is NOT exposed in
        the standard internal-user form layout, the list view, or
        the public portal lookup. (Setting display=false also
        prevents accidental exposure of internal duration metrics
        to external requesters via any future portal-widget that
        might call `GlideRecord.next()` and iterate columns.)
      - virtual=true: function fields are virtual (NOT stored in
        the underlying database column). The platform computes the
        value at query time from the input fields. Virtual fields
        do NOT trigger insert/update business rules, do NOT
        consume disk space on the case row, and do NOT participate
        in record-level audit history.
      - function_field=true: marks this dictionary entry as a
        ServiceNow Function Field (NOT a Calculated Value field).
        This is what makes the field reportable.
      - function_definition=glidefunction:datediff(closed_date,opened_date):
        the function-field formula, evaluated at query time on the
        platform's database engine.
      - max_length=40: standard ServiceNow ceiling for date/datetime/
        duration fields. Duration values internally render as
        `YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss` glide_duration strings of at most
        19 chars; 40 chars provides ample headroom.
      - choice=0: free-form Duration output (no choice list).
      - No reference target: this is a Duration field, not a
        Reference field.
      - text_index=false: Duration fields are not full-text-indexed.
      - unique=false: cases legitimately share durations.
      - calculation EMPTY: this is a FUNCTION FIELD, not a
        CALCULATED VALUE field. The `<calculation>` element is for
        the latter (a JavaScript `calculatedFieldValue(current)`
        function). Per ServiceNow platform semantics, a single
        dictionary entry uses EITHER `function_definition` OR
        `calculation`, never both. We use `function_definition`
        because only function fields are reportable.
      - No PII: the field stores no rows of data and contains no
        user identifiers, email addresses, or names.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      - This record MUST load AFTER:
          * ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml (parent table — `<name>`
            references the table by name)
          * ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_opened_date.xml (input
            field — referenced in <function_definition>)
          * ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_closed_date.xml (input
            field — referenced in <function_definition>)
      - This record MUST load BEFORE:
          * ../reports/x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml (the report
            references this field by element name in
            <aggregation_source>; without this dictionary entry,
            the report's aggregation source would not resolve and
            the widget would render "No data")
          * ../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_manager_view.xml
            (the dashboard references the avg_time_to_close report
            by name; once the report's aggregation source resolves,
            the widget renders the Duration AVG)
      - This record is INDEPENDENT of (does not depend on, and is
        not depended on by) `../business_rules/`,
        `../flows/sub_flows/`, `../script_includes/`, or any
        ../seed-data record. The function field's value is computed
        purely from the row's `opened_date` and `closed_date`
        columns at query time.

    DEPLOYMENT RE-VERIFICATION (POST-COMMIT)
    ========================================
    On a fresh PDI after Update Set commit:
      1. `Reports > View / Run` -> open `Average Time to Close`.
         Verify the single-score renders a Duration value
         (e.g., "5 Days 03:42:11"), NOT the "No data" placeholder.
      2. `Dashboards > Manager View`. Verify Widget 4 ("Average
         Time to Close") renders the same Duration value as the
         report standalone view.
      3. With Closed-status seed data showing realistic
         opened_date/closed_date pairs (e.g., demo case 06: opened
         10 days ago, closed 3 days ago), the AVG should produce a
         non-zero Duration. With both Closed demos populated, the
         AVG is the arithmetic mean of the two case durations.
-->
